<subSubSection id="D4E7FEB4AAD10894D8BD58D84C4EBBA3" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="714D48C7199226BE1E4F679B29AD0FDB" pageNumber="528">
Diagnosis A medium-sized yellow member of the 
<taxonomicName id="E75D0F63FE49B0ABA52613789B55E5E4" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33744" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole flavens Roger" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole flavens Roger" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavens">flavens</taxonomicName>
group distinguished by the nearly complete absence of sculpturing on the body, except for longitudinal carinulae on the anterior half of the head capsule of the major and minor, short and faint carinulae on the humerus of the major, and small patches of foveolae on the waist (major) or propodeal dorsum (minor). Propodeal spine short and suberect in both castes. Postpetiolar node of major broad and oval. Vertex of major (center of dorsum of head) with a faint circular brown spot.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8FF711AE0E0A3BD8669F22CC956C62D1" type="description">
<paragraph id="110D5AE3F2C2A401FA343C7104BB85F7" pageNumber="528">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName id="7D04FB62B428EDEEA8972F636588B16A" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181837" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole amabilis Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole amabilis Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amabilis">amabilis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4FD55F1E96C6B9E8D124A0420CF992A7" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181845" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole boliviana Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole boliviana Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boliviana">boliviana</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="43006279F9F676CBBA845DB6CDFCBC57" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181899" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole melastomae Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole melastomae Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melastomae">melastomae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="31358673FDEBC6C427A7DCBFE2AA823D" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181905" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole mixteca Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole mixteca Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mixteca">mixteca</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="82C9E550FABFC6AE49F09DE1433CE845" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181940" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole scitula Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole scitula Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scitula">scitula</taxonomicName>
, and especially 
<taxonomicName id="DBE9C89511812910E9B27C35D378B5BC" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34052" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole terresi Wheeler &amp; Mann" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole terresi Wheeler &amp; Mann" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="terresi">terresi</taxonomicName>
of Hispaniola. Most easily distinguished from the often sympatric 
<taxonomicName id="059B016C604755C9DDEF27660FA7FDA1" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33617" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole bicarinata Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole bicarinata Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicarinata">Pheidole bicarinata</taxonomicName>
by the absence of sculpture on the sides of the propodeum in the minor. In 
<taxonomicName id="4A766471A249FF592C5349872210AD28" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33617" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole bicarinata Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole bicarinata Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicarinata">bicarinata</taxonomicName>
minors these are foveolate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C02809DB44F9DECA6A7B19D489F6F155" pageNumber="528">Measurements (mm) Major (figured specimen above): HW 0.94, HL 1.10, SL 0.44, EL 0.12, PW 0.48. Minor (figured specimen above): HW 0.44, HL 0.48, SL 0.42, EL 0.06, PW 0.28. Color Major and minor: concolorous clear medium yellow. Minor head with a slightly reddish tinge.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="36BD330F3B258748397E5D54BD1784C5" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="C6A6F69517198253F4BB16626CB33690" pageNumber="528">
Range 
<taxonomicName id="368E137134C9259EECE5641757163B5A" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34074" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole tysoni Forel" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole tysoni Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tysoni">P. tysoni</taxonomicName>
appears to have a disjunct distribution. I have seen material from New York south to extreme northwest Georgia (Clayton, Rabun Co.) and westward through Tennessee and Kentucky to Barry Co., Kentucky. Stefan Cover has collected it in the Davis Mts. of western Texas at 1800 m, and at 1400-1800 m in the mountains of southern Arizona. Moody and Francke (1982) record a single colony found at 950 m in Hale Co., western Texas. Single series are recorded from near Juarez, Chihuahua, Mexico, and New
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B1E48CE0FCF8D386C85C5298CEA61981" pageNumber="529">Liberia, Louisiana, by William MacKay. The latter two records are somewhat anomalous in view of the otherwise montane and cooltemperate range of the species.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="893AEF788A6C973BE1C49D4B5F724173" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="F55A60B13A224D80BDE1A3EB3C4BA321" pageNumber="529">
Biology In New York, Stefan Cover (unpublished field notes) encountered colonies of 
<taxonomicName id="1625D9C6EF80CB1AF1B913895C59D1A2" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34074" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole tysoni Forel" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole tysoni Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="529" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tysoni">tysoni</taxonomicName>
in pure sandy soil of the Suffolk Co. pine barrens; in New York City, itself, he found a colony in the clayey soil of a residential lawn. In southern Arizona, he encountered the species in open woodlands variously composed of combinations of oak and juniper, usually with a grassy cover; nests were usually in the shade, either under stones or in open soil with or without craters of excavated earth. The soil varied from loam to fine sand. A nest Cover found in the Davis Mts. of Texas was beneath a stone in open oak-juniper-pinyon woodland. In Hale Co., Texas, Moody and Francke (1982) found a colony in the open ground of a vacant lot, the entrance surrounded by a 55-mm-wide tumulus of excavated soil. According to Cover, seeds are occasionally found in the nest, and workers tend aphids and collect floral nectar on low, herbaceous plants.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
